author: COMSOL
description:
The cathodic protection designer app can be used for simplified simulations of general cathodic protection designs, for cases when all different parts using different boundary conditions are separated as individual objects in the geometry.

The geometry is imported as a CAD file, fulfilling certain requirements. The user can then select each part of the geometry, and set boundary conditions according to a typical simulation scheme used by corrosion engineers for cathodic protection designs, which allows for solving of the initial, mean and final current densities. The results can be exported in a report either in HTML, Word or Powerpoint formats.

textmulti
settings.value:
The CAD file must consist of either solids or lines, or both. The file must be structured so that each surface or edge entity where you want to describe different properties or boundary conditions must be single objects. 

It is beneficial to collect similar surfaces, members, or anodes in the same object to keep the number of selections minimal.

It is also possible to import several (up to five) CAD models into the same geometry, such as one file for the cathode surfaces and one file for the anodes.

settings.name: textmulti
settings.value:
It is necessary to add an enclosing volume that contains the electrolyte. For cathodic protection models, this enclosing volume typically consists of two domains—one for seawater and one for the seabed or mud.
You can find a description of the settings for the different parameters in the settings window.

settings.name: textmulti
settings.value: Domain materials reflects the conductivity of water and mud in the enclosing volume. Select whether you domain is water or mud, and specify the respective conductivity in S/m.

settings.name: textmulti
settings.value: For boundary materials, you have different settings depending on whether the selection is an anode or a cathode.  Moreover, the application detects if a selection is an edge selection, and gives you an additional setting for the virtual radius of the edge.

settings.name: textmulti
settings.value:
The cathode material is specified by its three current densities: Initial, Mean and Final. This is according to design considerations in DNV RP-B401.  The boundary conditions become a fixed current density and you can choose which of these you want to consider in your computation in the Study-node.

You also may include the effect of coating breakdown by selecting the check box and specifying the coating breakdown parameters a and b. The equation becomes i=i0*(a+b*t[1/year]).

settings.name: textmulti
settings.value:
The anode material is specified by the equilibrium potential (Eeq) and the polarization curve gradient.
The expression used for the local current density out of the anode is:
i=Pg*(-phil-Eeq)
where phil is the electrolyte potential.

settings.name: textmulti
settings.value:
Default mesh parameters are defined by the size of the enclosing volume.  However, if you want a finer mesh, you may change these values.  
Also, if the meshing algorithm fails, setting a smaller minimum element size usually helps.

settings.name: textmulti
settings.value:
Select which parts of the study you want to include: Initial, Mean and Final.  
The design lifetime is included in the expressions for coating breakdown and anode radius, and should be set to the expected design lifetime of your structure.

settings.name: textmulti
settings.value:
Select which solver you want to use. Choose between: 
1. Direct Solver (More robust, but slower for larger models)
2. Iterative AMG (Iterative algebraic multigrid solver)
3. Iterative GMG (Iterative geometric multigrid solver)

settings.name: textmulti
settings.value: Select which study case and which plot you want to investigate.  Click in the graphics window to get the values at the picking point in the results data table.

settings.name: textmulti
settings.value:
Enter the project title and author name along with a summary of your findings.  
The report generator will automatically export images for your results along with information about the boundary conditions.
Save the report as either HTML, Word, or PowerPoint.
